### Introduction
Dark mode has become increasingly popular in web design as it provides a visually appealing and comfortable experience for users. CSS3 offers several features that allow developers to implement dark mode on their websites. This documentation will guide you through the process of implementing dark mode using CSS3.

### Objective and Scope
The objective of this documentation is to provide step-by-step instructions on implementing dark mode using CSS3. The scope of this documentation covers the necessary requirements, instructions, code snippets, troubleshooting tips, best practices, and recommendations for implementing dark mode.

### Requirements and Pre-requisites
To implement dark mode using CSS3, you will need the following:
- Basic knowledge of HTML and CSS
- A text editor or integrated development environment (IDE)
- A web browser to test your implementation

### Step-by-Step Instructions
1. Create a new CSS file or open an existing one in your text editor or IDE.
2. Add a class or ID selector to the HTML element(s) you want to apply dark mode to. For example, you can use `<body class="dark-mode">` or `<div id="dark-mode">`.
3. In your CSS file, define the styles for the dark mode. This can include changing the background color, text color, and other relevant styles. For example:

   ```css
   .dark-mode {
     background-color: #333;
     color: #fff;
   }
   ```

4. Add a media query to your CSS file to detect the user's preference for dark mode. This can be done using the `prefers-color-scheme` media feature. For example:

   ```css
   @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
     /* Styles for dark mode */
     .dark-mode {
       background-color: #333;
       color: #fff;
     }
   }
   ```

5. Save the CSS file and link it to your HTML file using the `<link>` element. For example:

   ```html
   <link rel="stylesheet" href="path/to/your/css/file.css">
   ```

6. Open your HTML file in a web browser to test the implementation of dark mode. If everything is set up correctly, the styles defined for dark mode should be applied when the user's preference is set to dark mode.

### Code Snippets and Commands
- CSS code snippet for defining dark mode styles:

  ```css
  .dark-mode {
    background-color: #333;
    color: #fff;
  }
  ```

- CSS code snippet for using the `prefers-color-scheme` media feature:

  ```css
  @media (prefers-color-scheme: dark) {
    /* Styles for dark mode */
    .dark-mode {
      background-color: #333;
      color: #fff;
    }
  }
  ```

### Troubleshooting and Common Issues
- Make sure you have correctly linked your CSS file to your HTML file using the `<link>` element.
- Check that your CSS selectors are targeting the correct HTML element(s).
- Verify that your CSS styles are defined correctly and are not conflicting with other styles.
- Test your implementation in different web browsers to ensure cross-browser compatibility.

### Best Practices and Recommendations
- Use descriptive class or ID names for your dark mode selectors to improve code readability.
- Consider using CSS variables to define colors and other styles. This allows for easier customization and maintenance.
- Test your dark mode implementation on different devices and screen sizes to ensure a consistent experience for all users.

### Summary and Conclusion
Implementing dark mode using CSS3 is a straightforward process that involves defining styles for dark mode and using media queries to detect the user's preference. By following the step-by-step instructions provided in this documentation, you can easily implement dark mode on your website. Remember to test your implementation thoroughly and follow best practices for optimal results.
